  "articleSummary": "The article argues that the real danger of AI writing is not poor quality but plausible smoothness that masks a lack of genuine point of view. The author, a technical writer and educator, describes shifting from accepting AI’s first drafts as finished artifacts to using it as a “pressure tool” that generates surfaces and alternatives—such as organizing notes, producing wrong answers, or interrogating drafts—while reserving human judgment for taste, decisions, and honest prose. Key metaphors include “clay” (AI produces raw material; the human decides the shape) and “bland professional paste” (prose that sounds correct but lacks authenticity). The tone is reflective and pragmatic, with a critical but not dismissive stance, aimed at writers and content creators who want to integrate AI without losing editorial integrity.",
